September 14, 1914 was a Monday and it was the 257th day of the year 1914 in the Gregorian calendar.

September 14, 1914 can also be written as 9/14/1914 in the US and as 14/9/1914 in UK and Europe.

Moon phase

The moon phase on September 14, 1914 was Waning crescent.

The moon phase refers to the appearance of the Moon in the night sky on September 14, 1914 and is determined by the portion of the Moon's illuminated surface that is visible from Earth.

An observer located in New York City on September 14, 1914 at 10pm, would see the moon, being 20% full, rising at 11:10 pm and setting at 03:54 pm.

The previous full moon was on Sep 04, 1914 while the next full moon would come on Oct 04, 1914.

What is special about September 14th?

September 14th refers to a specific date on the calendar, which is the 14th day of the month of September. It is a date that occurs annually and is part of the Gregorian calendar, which is widely used around the world.

Over the years several events happened on September 14th, such as:

2018 - Syrian civil war: idlib residents demonstrate against president bashar al-assad's government.

2017 - Iraqi civil war 2017 nasiriyah attacks: at least 50 people were killed and 87 more were injured in multiple attacks by isil members on the outskirts nasiriyah, in the southern dhi qar governorate.
